          <div class="faq-a">Yes, you can substitute oil for butter in most baking recipes. Use ¾ the amount of oil as butter (e.g., ¾ cup oil for 1 cup butter) since oil is 100% fat while butter is about 80% fat. Baked goods made with oil tend to be moister and denser. Use neutral oils like canola or vegetable oil for most recipes, or coconut oil for a richer flavor.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">How do I make buttermilk substitute at home?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">To make a buttermilk substitute, add 1 tablespoon of white vinegar or lemon juice to a measuring cup, then fill to the 1-cup mark with regular milk. Stir and let it sit for 5–10 minutes until it curdles slightly. This works in any recipe calling for buttermilk, including pancakes, biscuits, and cakes.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">What can I use instead of all-purpose flour for gluten-free baking?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">For gluten-free baking, use a 1:1 gluten-free flour blend (like Bob's Red Mill or King Arthur) as the easiest swap. Almond flour works well for cookies and quick breads — use ¾ cup almond flour plus ¼ cup starch per cup of AP flour. Oat flour (made from certified GF oats) is another option at a 1:1 ratio but may need extra binding from xanthan gum (½ tsp per cup of flour).</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">Can I replace sugar with honey in baking?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Yes, replace 1 cup of sugar with ¾ cup honey. Since honey adds moisture, reduce other liquids in the recipe by 3–4 tablespoons per cup of honey used, and lower the oven temperature by 25°F (14°C) to prevent over-browning. Honey also adds a distinct flavor that works well in quick breads, muffins, and cookies but may not be ideal for delicate cakes.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-q">What is the best dairy-free substitute for milk in baking?</div>
          <div class="faq-a">Oat milk is widely considered the best dairy-free milk substitute for baking because its creamy texture and neutral flavor closely mimic whole milk. Use it at a 1:1 ratio. Soy milk is another excellent option with similar protein content. Almond milk works too but is thinner, so it's best in recipes where milk isn't the primary liquid.</div>
